# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: david-chapman-chemist
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:david-chapman-chemist/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] The ***Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society*** is an academic journal on the history of science published annually by the Royal Society.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] It publishes obituaries of Fellows of the Royal Society.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] It was established in 1932 as *Obituary Notices of Fellows of the Royal Society* and obtained its current title in 1955, with volume numbering restarting at 1.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] Prior to 1932, obituaries were published in the *Proceedings of the Royal Society*.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] The memoirs are a significant historical record and most include a full bibliography of works by the subjects.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] The memoirs are often written by a scientist of the next generation, often one of the subject's own former students, or a close colleague.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] In many cases the author is also a Fellow.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] Notable biographies published in this journal include Albert Einstein, Alan Turing, Bertrand Russell, Claude Shannon, Clement Attlee, Ernst Mayr, and Erwin Schrödinger.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] Each year, around 40 to 50 memoirs of deceased Fellows of the Royal Society are collated by the Editor-in-Chief, currently Malcolm Longair, who succeeded Trevor Stuart in 2016.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] All contents are freely available to read.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] The **Chapman–Jouguet condition** holds approximately in detonation waves in high explosives.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] It states that the detonation propagates at a velocity at which the reacting gases just reach sonic velocity (in the frame of the leading shock wave) as the reaction ceases.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] David Chapman and Émile Jouguet originally (c.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] 1900) stated the condition for an infinitesimally thin detonation.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] A physical interpretation of the condition is usually based on the later modelling (c.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] 1943) by Yakov Borisovich Zel'dovich, John von Neumann, and Werner Döring (the so-called ZND detonation model).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] In more detail (in the ZND model) in the frame of the leading shock of the detonation wave, gases enter at supersonic velocity and are compressed through the shock to a high-density, subsonic flow.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] This sudden change in pressure initiates the chemical (or sometimes, as in steam explosions, physical) energy release.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] The energy release re-accelerates the flow back to the local speed of sound.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] It can be shown fairly simply, from the one-dimensional gas equations for steady flow, that the reaction must cease at the sonic ("CJ") plane, or there would be discontinuously large pressure gradients at that point.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] The sonic plane forms a so-called choke point that enables the lead shock, and reaction zone, to travel at a constant velocity, undisturbed by the expansion of gases in the rarefaction region beyond the CJ plane.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] This simple one-dimensional model is quite successful in explaining detonations.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] However, observations of the structure of real chemical detonations show a complex three-dimensional structure, with parts of the wave traveling faster than average, and others slower.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] Indeed, such waves are quenched as their structure is destroyed.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] The Wood–Kirkwood detonation theory can correct for some of these limitations.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] Here the subscript 1 and 2 identifies flow properties (pressure p , density $\rho$ ) upstream and downstream of the wave and m is the constant mass flux and q is the heat released in the wave.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] where M is the Mach number and c is the speed of sound, in other words, downstream flow is sonic with respect to the Chapman-Jouguet wave.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chapman-jouguet-condition] The upper sign applies for the **Upper Chapman-Jouguet** point (detonation) and the lower sign applies for the **Lower Chapman-Jouguet** point (deflagration).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In the scope of its subject, chemistry occupies an intermediate position between physics and biology.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] It is sometimes called the central science because it provides a foundation for understanding both basic and applied scientific disciplines at a fundamental level.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Chemistry has existed under various names since ancient times.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] It has evolved, and now chemistry encompasses various areas of specialisation, or subdisciplines, that continue to increase in number and interrelate to create further interdisciplinary fields of study.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The applications of various fields of chemistry are used frequently for economic purposes in the chemical industry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The word *chemistry* comes from a modification during the Renaissance of the word *alchemy,* which referred to an earlier set of practices that encompassed elements of chemistry, metallurgy, philosophy, astrology, astronomy, mysticism, and medicine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Alchemy is often associated with the quest to turn lead or other base metals into gold, though alchemists were also interested in many of the questions of modern chemistry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The modern word *alchemy* in turn is derived from the Arabic word *al-kīmīā* (الكیمیاء).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] This may have Egyptian origins since *al-kīmīā* is derived from the Ancient Greek χημία, which is in turn derived from the word *Kemet*, which is the ancient name of Egypt in the Egyptian language.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Alternately, *al-kīmīā* may derive from χημεία 'cast together'.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The current model of atomic structure is the quantum mechanical model.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Traditional chemistry starts with the study of elementary particles, atoms, molecules, substances, metals, crystals and other aggregates of matter.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Matter can be studied in solid, liquid, gas and plasma states, in isolation or in combination.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The interactions, reactions and transformations that are studied in chemistry are usually the result of interactions between atoms, leading to rearrangements of the chemical bonds which hold atoms together.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Such behaviors are studied in a chemistry laboratory.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The chemistry laboratory stereotypically uses various forms of laboratory glassware.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] However glassware is not central to chemistry, and a great deal of experimental (as well as applied/industrial) chemistry is done without it.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A chemical reaction is a transformation of some substances into one or more different substances.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The basis of such a chemical transformation is the rearrangement of electrons in the chemical bonds between atoms.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] It can be symbolically depicted through a chemical equation, which usually involves atoms as subjects.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The number of atoms on the left and the right in the equation for a chemical transformation is equal.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] (When the number of atoms on either side is unequal, the transformation is referred to as a nuclear reaction or radioactive decay.) The type of chemical reactions a substance may undergo and the energy changes that may accompany it are constrained by certain basic rules, known as chemical laws.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Energy and entropy considerations are invariably important in almost all chemical studies.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Chemical substances are classified in terms of their structure, phase, as well as their chemical compositions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] They can be analyzed using the tools of chemical analysis, e.g. spectroscopy and chromatography.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Scientists engaged in chemical research are known as chemists.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Most chemists specialize in one or more sub-disciplines.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In chemistry, matter is defined as anything that has rest mass and volume (it takes up space) and is made up of particles.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The particles that make up matter have rest mass as well – not all particles have rest mass, such as the photon.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Matter can be a pure chemical substance or a mixture of substances.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The atom is the basic unit of chemistry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] It consists of a dense core called the atomic nucleus surrounded by a space occupied by an electron cloud.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The nucleus is made up of positively charged protons and uncharged neutrons (together called nucleons), while the electron cloud consists of negatively charged electrons which orbit the nucleus.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In a neutral atom, the negatively charged electrons balance out the positive charge of the protons.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The nucleus is dense; the mass of a nucleon is approximately 1,836 times that of an electron, yet the radius of an atom is about 10,000 times that of its nucleus.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The atom is also the smallest entity that can be envisaged to retain the chemical properties of the element, such as electronegativity, ionization potential, preferred oxidation state(s), coordination number, and preferred types of bonds to form (e.g., metallic, ionic, covalent).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A chemical element is a pure substance which is composed of a single type of atom, characterized by its particular number of protons in the nuclei of its atoms, known as the atomic number and represented by the symbol *Z*.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The mass number is the sum of the number of protons and neutrons in a nucleus.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Although all the nuclei of all atoms belonging to one element will have the same atomic number, they may not necessarily have the same mass number; atoms of an element which have different mass numbers are known as isotopes.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] For example, all atoms with 6 protons in their nuclei are atoms of the chemical element carbon, but atoms of carbon may have mass numbers of 12 or 13.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The standard presentation of the chemical elements is in the periodic table, which orders elements by atomic number.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The periodic table is arranged in groups, or columns, and periods, or rows.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The periodic table is useful in identifying periodic trends.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A *compound* is a pure chemical substance composed of more than one element.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The properties of a compound bear little similarity to those of its elements.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The standard nomenclature of compounds is set by the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Organic compounds are named according to the organic nomenclature system.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The names for inorganic compounds are created according to the inorganic nomenclature system.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] When a compound has more than one component, then they are divided into two classes, the electropositive and the electronegative components.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In addition the Chemical Abstracts Service (CAS) has devised a method to index chemical substances.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In this scheme each chemical substance is identifiable by a number known as its CAS registry number.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A *molecule* is the smallest indivisible portion of a pure chemical substance that has its unique set of chemical properties, that is, its potential to undergo a certain set of chemical reactions with other substances.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] However, this definition only works well for substances that are composed of molecules, which is not true of many substances (see below).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Molecules are typically a set of atoms bound together by covalent bonds, such that the structure is electrically neutral and all valence electrons are paired with other electrons either in bonds or in lone pairs.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Thus, molecules exist as electrically neutral units, unlike ions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] When this rule is broken, giving the "molecule" a charge, the result is sometimes named a molecular ion or a polyatomic ion.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] However, the discrete and separate nature of the molecular concept usually requires that molecular ions be present only in well-separated form, such as a directed beam in a vacuum in a mass spectrometer.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Charged polyatomic collections residing in solids (for example, common sulfate or nitrate ions) are generally not considered "molecules" in chemistry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Some molecules contain one or more unpaired electrons, creating radicals.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Most radicals are comparatively reactive, but some, such as nitric oxide (NO) can be stable.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The "inert" or noble gas elements (helium, neon, argon, krypton, xenon and radon) are composed of lone atoms as their smallest discrete unit, but the other isolated chemical elements consist of either molecules or networks of atoms bonded to each other in some way.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Identifiable molecules compose familiar substances such as water, air, and many organic compounds like alcohol, sugar, gasoline, and the various pharmaceuticals.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] However, not all substances or chemical compounds consist of discrete molecules, and indeed most of the solid substances that make up the solid crust, mantle, and core of the Earth are chemical compounds without molecules.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] These other types of substances, such as ionic compounds and network solids, are organized in such a way as to lack the existence of identifiable molecules *per se*.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Instead, these substances are discussed in terms of formula units or unit cells as the smallest repeating structure within the substance.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Examples of such substances are mineral salts (such as table salt), solids like carbon and diamond, metals, and familiar silica and silicate minerals such as quartz and granite.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] One of the main characteristics of a molecule is its geometry often called its structure.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] While the structure of diatomic, triatomic or tetra-atomic molecules may be trivial, (linear, angular pyramidal etc.) the structure of polyatomic molecules, that are constituted of more than six atoms (of several elements) can be crucial for its chemical nature.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A chemical substance is a kind of matter with a definite composition and set of properties.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A collection of substances is called a mixture.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Examples of mixtures are air and alloys.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The mole is a unit of measurement that denotes an amount of substance (also called chemical amount).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] One mole is defined to contain exactly 6.02214076×1023 particles (atoms, molecules, ions, or electrons), where the number of particles per mole is known as the Avogadro constant.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Molar concentration is the amount of a particular substance per volume of solution, and is commonly reported in mol/dm3.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In addition to the specific chemical properties that distinguish different chemical classifications, chemicals can exist in several phases.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] For the most part, the chemical classifications are independent of these bulk phase classifications; however, some more exotic phases are incompatible with certain chemical properties.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A *phase* is a set of states of a chemical system that have similar bulk structural properties, over a range of conditions, such as pressure or temperature.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Physical properties, such as density and refractive index tend to fall within values characteristic of the phase.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The phase of matter is defined by the *phase transition*, which is when energy put into or taken out of the system goes into rearranging the structure of the system, instead of changing the bulk conditions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Sometimes the distinction between phases can be continuous instead of having a discrete boundary; in this case the matter is considered to be in a supercritical state.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] When three states meet based on the conditions, it is known as a triple point and since this is invariant, it is a convenient way to define a set of conditions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The most familiar examples of phases are solids, liquids, and gases.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Many substances exhibit multiple solid phases.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] For example, there are three phases of solid iron (alpha, gamma, and delta) that vary based on temperature and pressure.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A principal difference between solid phases is the crystal structure, or arrangement, of the atoms.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Another phase commonly encountered in the study of chemistry is the *aqueous* phase, which is the state of substances dissolved in aqueous solution (that is, in water).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Less familiar phases include plasmas, Bose–Einstein condensates and fermionic condensates and the paramagnetic and ferromagnetic phases of magnetic materials.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] While most familiar phases deal with three-dimensional systems, it is also possible to define analogs in two-dimensional systems, which has received attention for its relevance to systems in biology.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Atoms sticking together in molecules or crystals are said to be bonded with one another.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A chemical bond may be visualized as the multipole balance between the positive charges in the nuclei and the negative charges oscillating about them.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] More than simple attraction and repulsion, the energies and distributions characterize the availability of an electron to bond to another atom.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The chemical bond can be a covalent bond, an ionic bond, a hydrogen bond or just because of Van der Waals force.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Each of these kinds of bonds is ascribed to some potential.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] These potentials create the interactions which hold atoms together in molecules or crystals.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In many simple compounds, valence bond theory, the Valence Shell Electron Pair Repulsion model (VSEPR), and the concept of oxidation number can be used to explain molecular structure and composition.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] An ionic bond is formed when a metal loses one or more of its electrons, becoming a positively charged cation, and the electrons are then gained by the non-metal atom, becoming a negatively charged anion.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The two oppositely charged ions attract one another, and the ionic bond is the electrostatic force of attraction between them.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] For example, sodium (Na), a metal, loses one electron to become an Na+ cation while chlorine (Cl), a non-metal, gains this electron to become Cl−.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The ions are held together due to electrostatic attraction, and that compound sodium chloride (NaCl), or common table salt, is formed.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In a covalent bond, one or more pairs of valence electrons are shared by two atoms: the resulting electrically neutral group of bonded atoms is termed a molecule.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Atoms will share valence electrons in such a way as to create a noble gas electron configuration (eight electrons in their outermost shell) for each atom.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Atoms that tend to combine in such a way that they each have eight electrons in their valence shell are said to follow the octet rule.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Similarly, theories from classical physics can be used to predict many ionic structures.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] With more complicated compounds, such as metal complexes, valence bond theory is less applicable and alternative approaches, such as the molecular orbital theory, are generally used.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In the context of chemistry, energy is an attribute of a substance as a consequence of its atomic, molecular or aggregate structure.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Since a chemical transformation is accompanied by a change in one or more of these kinds of structures, it is invariably accompanied by an increase or decrease of energy of the substances involved.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Some energy is transferred between the surroundings and the reactants of the reaction in the form of heat or light; thus the products of a reaction may have more or less energy than the reactants.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A reaction is said to be exergonic if the final state is lower on the energy scale than the initial state; in the case of endergonic reactions the situation is the reverse.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A reaction is said to be exothermic if the reaction releases heat to the surroundings; in the case of endothermic reactions, the reaction absorbs heat from the surroundings.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Chemical reactions are invariably not possible unless the reactants surmount an energy barrier known as the activation energy.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The *speed* of a chemical reaction (at given temperature T) is related to the activation energy E, by the Boltzmann's population factor $e^{-E/kT}$ – that is the probability of a molecule to have energy greater than or equal to E at the given temperature T.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] This exponential dependence of a reaction rate on temperature is known as the Arrhenius equation.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The activation energy necessary for a chemical reaction to occur can be in the form of heat, light, electricity or mechanical force in the form of ultrasound.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A related concept free energy, which also incorporates entropy considerations, is a very useful means for predicting the feasibility of a reaction and determining the state of equilibrium of a chemical reaction, in chemical thermodynamics.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A reaction is feasible only if the total change in the Gibbs free energy is negative, $\Delta G\leq 0\,$ ; if it is equal to zero the chemical reaction is said to be at equilibrium.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] There exist only limited possible states of energy for electrons, atoms and molecules.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] These are determined by the rules of quantum mechanics, which require quantization of energy of a bound system.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The atoms/molecules in a higher energy state are said to be excited.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The molecules/atoms of substance in an excited energy state are often much more reactive; that is, more amenable to chemical reactions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The phase of a substance is invariably determined by its energy and the energy of its surroundings.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] When the intermolecular forces of a substance are such that the energy of the surroundings is not sufficient to overcome them, it occurs in a more ordered phase like liquid or solid as is the case with water (H2O); a liquid at room temperature because its molecules are bound by hydrogen bonds.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Whereas hydrogen sulfide (H2S) is a gas at room temperature and standard pressure, as its molecules are bound by weaker dipole–dipole interactions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The transfer of energy from one chemical substance to another depends on the *size* of energy quanta emitted from one substance.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] However, heat energy is often transferred more easily from almost any substance to another because the phonons responsible for vibrational and rotational energy levels in a substance have much less energy than photons invoked for the electronic energy transfer.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Thus, because vibrational and rotational energy levels are more closely spaced than electronic energy levels, heat is more easily transferred between substances relative to light or other forms of electronic energy.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] For example, ultraviolet electromagnetic radiation is not transferred with as much efficacy from one substance to another as thermal or electrical energy.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The existence of characteristic energy levels for different chemical substances is useful for their identification by the analysis of spectral lines.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Different kinds of spectra are often used in chemical spectroscopy, e.g.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Spectroscopy is also used to identify the composition of remote objects – like stars and distant galaxies – by analyzing their radiation spectra.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The term chemical energy is often used to indicate the potential of a chemical substance to undergo a transformation through a chemical reaction or to transform other chemical substances.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] When a chemical substance is transformed as a result of its interaction with another substance or with energy, a chemical reaction is said to have occurred.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A *chemical reaction* is therefore a concept related to the "reaction" of a substance when it comes in close contact with another, whether as a mixture or a solution; exposure to some form of energy, or both.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] It results in some energy exchange between the constituents of the reaction as well as with the system environment, which may be designed vessels—often laboratory glassware.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Chemical reactions can result in the formation or dissociation of molecules, that is, molecules breaking apart to form two or more molecules or rearrangement of atoms within or across molecules.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Chemical reactions usually involve the making or breaking of chemical bonds.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Oxidation, reduction, dissociation, acid–base neutralization and molecular rearrangement are some examples of common chemical reactions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A chemical reaction can be symbolically depicted through a chemical equation.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] While in a non-nuclear chemical reaction the number and kind of atoms on both sides of the equation are equal, for a nuclear reaction this holds true only for the nuclear particles viz. protons and neutrons.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The sequence of steps in which the reorganization of chemical bonds may be taking place in the course of a chemical reaction is called its mechanism.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A chemical reaction can be envisioned to take place in a number of steps, each of which may have a different speed.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Many reaction intermediates with variable stability can thus be envisaged during the course of a reaction.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Reaction mechanisms are proposed to explain the kinetics and the relative product mix of a reaction.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Many physical chemists specialize in exploring and proposing the mechanisms of various chemical reactions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Several empirical rules, like the Woodward–Hoffmann rules often come in handy while proposing a mechanism for a chemical reaction.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] According to the IUPAC gold book, a chemical reaction is "a process that results in the interconversion of chemical species." Accordingly, a chemical reaction may be an elementary reaction or a stepwise reaction.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] An additional caveat is made, in that this definition includes cases where the interconversion of conformers is experimentally observable.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Such detectable chemical reactions normally involve sets of molecular entities as indicated by this definition, but it is often conceptually convenient to use the term also for changes involving single molecular entities (i.e.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] An *ion* is a charged species, an atom or a molecule, that has lost or gained one or more electrons.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] When an atom loses an electron and thus has more protons than electrons, the atom is a positively charged ion or cation.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] When an atom gains an electron and thus has more electrons than protons, the atom is a negatively charged ion or anion.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Cations and anions can form a crystalline lattice of neutral salts, such as the Na+ and Cl− ions forming sodium chloride, or NaCl.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Examples of polyatomic ions that do not split up during acid–base reactions are hydroxide (OH−) and phosphate (PO43−).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Plasma is composed of gaseous matter that has been completely ionized, usually through high temperature.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A substance can often be classified as an acid or a base.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] There are several different theories which explain acid–base behavior.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The simplest is Arrhenius theory, which states that an acid is a substance that produces hydronium ions when it is dissolved in water, and a base is one that produces hydroxide ions when dissolved in water.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] According to Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory, acids are substances that donate a positive hydrogen ion to another substance in a chemical reaction; by extension, a base is the substance which receives that hydrogen ion.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A third common theory is Lewis acid–base theory, which is based on the formation of new chemical bonds.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Lewis theory explains that an acid is a substance which is capable of accepting a pair of electrons from another substance during the process of bond formation, while a base is a substance which can provide a pair of electrons to form a new bond.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] There are several other ways in which a substance may be classified as an acid or a base, as is evident in the history of this concept.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Acid strength is commonly measured by two methods.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] One measurement, based on the Arrhenius definition of acidity, is pH, which is a measurement of the hydronium ion concentration in a solution, as expressed on a negative logarithmic scale.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Thus, solutions that have a low pH have a high hydronium ion concentration and can be said to be more acidic.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The other measurement, based on the Brønsted–Lowry definition, is the acid dissociation constant (Ka), which measures the relative ability of a substance to act as an acid under the Brønsted–Lowry definition of an acid.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] That is, substances with a higher Ka are more likely to donate hydrogen ions in chemical reactions than those with lower Ka values.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Redox (*red*uction-*ox*idation) reactions include all chemical reactions in which atoms have their oxidation state changed by either gaining electrons (reduction) or losing electrons (oxidation).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Substances that have the ability to oxidize other substances are said to be oxidative and are known as oxidizing agents, oxidants or oxidizers.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] An oxidant removes electrons from another substance.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Similarly, substances that have the ability to reduce other substances are said to be reductive and are known as reducing agents, reductants, or reducers.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A reductant transfers electrons to another substance and is thus oxidized itself.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] And because it "donates" electrons it is also called an electron donor.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Oxidation and reduction properly refer to a change in oxidation number—the actual transfer of electrons may never occur.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Thus, oxidation is better defined as an increase in oxidation number, and reduction as a decrease in oxidation number.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A system of chemical substances at equilibrium, even though having an unchanging composition, is most often not static; molecules of the substances continue to react with one another thus giving rise to a dynamic equilibrium.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Thus the concept describes the state in which the parameters such as chemical composition remain unchanged over time.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Chemical reactions are governed by certain laws, which have become fundamental concepts in chemistry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The history of chemistry spans a period from the ancient past to the present.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Since several millennia BC, civilizations were using technologies that would eventually form the basis of the various branches of chemistry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Examples include extracting metals from ores, making pottery and glazes, fermenting beer and wine, extracting chemicals from plants for medicine and perfume, rendering fat into soap, making glass, and making alloys like bronze.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Chemistry was preceded by its protoscience, alchemy, which operated a non-scientific approach to understanding the constituents of matter and their interactions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Despite being unsuccessful in explaining the nature of matter and its transformations, alchemists set the stage for modern chemistry by performing experiments and recording the results.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Robert Boyle, although skeptical of elements and convinced of alchemy, played a key part in elevating the "sacred art" as an independent, fundamental and philosophical discipline in his work *The Sceptical Chymist* (1661).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] While both alchemy and chemistry are concerned with matter and its transformations, the crucial difference was given by the scientific method that chemists employed in their work.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Chemistry, as a body of knowledge distinct from alchemy, became an established science with the work of Antoine Lavoisier, who developed a law of conservation of mass that demanded careful measurement and quantitative observations of chemical phenomena.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The history of chemistry afterwards is intertwined with the history of thermodynamics, especially through the work of Willard Gibbs.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The definition of chemistry has changed over time, as new discoveries and theories add to the functionality of the science.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The term "chymistry", in the view of noted scientist Robert Boyle in 1661, meant the subject of the material principles of mixed bodies.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In 1663, the chemist Christopher Glaser described "chymistry" as a scientific art, by which one learns to dissolve bodies, and draw from them the different substances on their composition, and how to unite them again, and exalt them to a higher perfection.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The 1730 definition of the word "chemistry", as used by Georg Ernst Stahl, meant the art of resolving mixed, compound, or aggregate bodies into their principles; and of composing such bodies from those principles.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In 1837, Jean-Baptiste Dumas considered the word "chemistry" to refer to the science concerned with the laws and effects of molecular forces.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] This definition further evolved until, in 1947, it came to mean the science of substances: their structure, their properties, and the reactions that change them into other substances—a characterization accepted by Linus Pauling.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] More recently, in 1998, Professor Raymond Chang broadened the definition of "chemistry" to mean the study of matter and the changes it undergoes.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Early civilizations, such as the Egyptians, Babylonians, and Indians, amassed practical knowledge concerning the arts of metallurgy, pottery and dyes, but did not develop a systematic theory.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] A basic chemical hypothesis first emerged in Classical Greece with the theory of four elements as propounded definitively by Aristotle stating that fire, air, earth and water were the fundamental elements from which everything is formed as a combination.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Greek atomism dates back to 440 BC, arising in works by philosophers such as Democritus and Epicurus.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In 50 BCE, the Roman philosopher Lucretius expanded upon the theory in his poem *De rerum natura* (On The Nature of Things).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Unlike modern concepts of science, Greek atomism was purely philosophical in nature, with little concern for empirical observations and no concern for chemical experiments.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] An early form of the idea of conservation of mass is the notion that "Nothing comes from nothing" in Ancient Greek philosophy, which can be found in Empedocles (approx.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In the Hellenistic world the art of alchemy first proliferated, mingling magic and occultism into the study of natural substances with the ultimate goal of transmuting elements into gold and discovering the elixir of eternal life.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Work, particularly the development of distillation, continued in the early Byzantine period with the most famous practitioner being the 4th century Greek-Egyptian Zosimos of Panopolis.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Alchemy continued to be developed and practised throughout the Arab world after the Muslim conquests, and from there, and from the Byzantine remnants, diffused into medieval and Renaissance Europe through Latin translations.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The Arabic works attributed to Jabir ibn Hayyan introduced a systematic classification of chemical substances, and provided instructions for deriving an inorganic compound (sal ammoniac or ammonium chloride) from organic substances (such as plants, blood, and hair) by chemical means.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Later influential Muslim philosophers, such as Abū al-Rayhān al-Bīrūnī and Avicenna disputed the theories of alchemy, particularly the theory of the transmutation of metals.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Improvements of the refining of ores and their extractions to smelt metals was widely used source of information for early chemists in the 16th century, among them Georg Agricola (1494–1555), who published his major work *De re metallica* in 1556.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] His work, describing highly developed and complex processes of mining metal ores and metal extraction, were the pinnacle of metallurgy during that time.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] His approach removed all mysticism associated with the subject, creating the practical base upon which others could and would build.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The work describes the many kinds of furnaces used to smelt ore, and stimulated interest in minerals and their composition.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Agricola has been described as the "father of metallurgy" and the founder of geology as a scientific discipline.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Under the influence of the Scientific Revolution and its new empirical methods propounded by Sir Francis Bacon and others, a group of chemists at Oxford, Robert Boyle, Robert Hooke and John Mayow began to reshape the old alchemical traditions into a scientific discipline.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Boyle in particular questioned some commonly held chemical theories and argued for chemical practitioners to be more "philosophical" and less commercially focused in *The Sceptical Chemyst*.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] He formulated Boyle's law, rejected the classical "four elements" and proposed a mechanistic alternative of atoms and chemical reactions that could be subject to rigorous experiment.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In the following decades, many important discoveries were made, such as the nature of 'air' which was discovered to be composed of many different gases.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The Scottish chemist Joseph Black and the Flemish Jan Baptist van Helmont discovered carbon dioxide, or what Black called 'fixed air' in 1754; Henry Cavendish discovered hydrogen and elucidated its properties and Joseph Priestley and, independently, Carl Wilhelm Scheele isolated pure oxygen.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The theory of phlogiston (a substance at the root of all combustion) was propounded by the German Georg Ernst Stahl in the early 18th century and was only overturned by the end of the century by the French chemist Antoine Lavoisier, the chemical analogue of Newton in physics.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Lavoisier did more than any other to establish the new science on proper theoretical footing, by elucidating the principle of conservation of mass and developing a new system of chemical nomenclature used to this day.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] English scientist John Dalton proposed the modern theory of atoms; that all substances are composed of indivisible 'atoms' of matter and that different atoms have varying atomic weights.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The development of the electrochemical theory of chemical combinations occurred in the early 19th century as the result of the work of two scientists in particular, Jöns Jacob Berzelius and Humphry Davy, made possible by the prior invention of the voltaic pile by Alessandro Volta.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Davy discovered nine new elements including the alkali metals by extracting them from their oxides with electric current.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] British William Prout first proposed ordering all the elements by their atomic weight as all atoms had a weight that was an exact multiple of the atomic weight of hydrogen.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Newlands devised an early table of elements, which was then developed into the modern periodic table of elements in the 1860s by Dmitri Mendeleev and independently by several other scientists including Julius Lothar Meyer.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The inert gases, later called the noble gases were discovered by William Ramsay in collaboration with Lord Rayleigh at the end of the century, thereby filling in the basic structure of the table.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Organic chemistry was developed by Justus von Liebig and others, following Friedrich Wöhler's synthesis of urea.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Other crucial 19th century advances were; an understanding of valence bonding (Edward Frankland in 1852) and the application of thermodynamics to chemistry (J.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Gibbs and Svante Arrhenius in the 1870s).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] At the turn of the twentieth century the theoretical underpinnings of chemistry were finally understood due to a series of remarkable discoveries that succeeded in probing and discovering the very nature of the internal structure of atoms.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Thomson of the University of Cambridge discovered the electron and soon after the French scientist Becquerel as well as the couple Pierre and Marie Curie investigated the phenomenon of radioactivity.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] His work on atomic structure was improved on by his students, the Danish physicist Niels Bohr, the Englishman Henry Moseley and the German Otto Hahn, who went on to father the emerging nuclear chemistry and discovered nuclear fission.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The electronic theory of chemical bonds and molecular orbitals was developed by the American scientists Linus Pauling and Gilbert N.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The year 2011 was declared by the United Nations as the International Year of Chemistry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] As one of the United Nations' many International Year designations, it was an initiative to broaden outreach and public understanding in chemistry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The year was chosen as the 100th anniversary of Marie Curie's receipt of the Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Several years later, in 2019, the UN declared the International Year of the Periodic Table.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] In the practice of chemistry, **pure chemistry** is the study of the fundamental principles of chemistry, while **applied chemistry** applies that knowledge to develop technology and solve real-world problems.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] Chemistry is typically divided into several major sub-disciplines.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] There are also several main cross-disciplinary and more specialized fields of chemistry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The chemical industry represents an important economic activity worldwide.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chemistry] The global top 50 chemical producers in 2013 had sales of US$980.5 billion with a profit margin of 10.3%.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] However, the nature of free chlorine gas as a separate substance was only recognised around 1630 by Jan Baptist van Helmont.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Carl Wilhelm Scheele wrote a description of chlorine gas in 1774, supposing it to be an oxide of a new element.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In 1809, chemists suggested that the gas might be a pure element, and this was confirmed by Sir Humphry Davy in 1810, who named it after the Ancient Greek χλωρός (*khlōrós*, "pale green") because of its colour.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Because of its great reactivity, all chlorine in the Earth's crust is in the form of ionic chloride compounds, which includes table salt.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is the second-most abundant halogen (after fluorine) and 20th most abundant element in Earth's crust.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] These crystal deposits are nevertheless dwarfed by the huge reserves of chloride in seawater.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Elemental chlorine is commercially produced from brine by electrolysis, predominantly in the chloralkali process.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The high oxidising potential of elemental chlorine led to the development of commercial bleaches and disinfectants, and a reagent for many processes in the chemical industry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine is used in the manufacture of a wide range of consumer products, about two-thirds of them organic chemicals such as polyvinyl chloride (PVC), many intermediates for the production of plastics, and other end products which do not contain the element.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] As a common disinfectant, elemental chlorine and chlorine-generating compounds are used more directly in swimming pools to keep them sanitary.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Elemental chlorine at high concentration is extremely dangerous, and poisonous to most living organisms.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] As a chemical warfare agent, chlorine was first used in World War I as a poison gas weapon.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In the form of chloride ions, chlorine is necessary to all known species of life.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Other types of chlorine compounds are rare in living organisms, and artificially produced chlorinated organics range from inert to toxic.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In the upper atmosphere, chlorine-containing organic molecules such as chlorofluorocarbons have been implicated in ozone depletion.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Small quantities of elemental chlorine are generated by oxidation of chloride ions in neutrophils as part of an immune system response against bacteria.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The most common compound of chlorine, sodium chloride, has been known since ancient times; archaeologists have found evidence that rock salt was used as early as 3000 BC and brine as early as 6000 BC.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Around 900, the authors of the Arabic writings attributed to Jabir ibn Hayyan (Latin: Geber) and the Persian physician and alchemist Abu Bakr al-Razi (c.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] 865–925, Latin: Rhazes) were experimenting with sal ammoniac (ammonium chloride), which when it was distilled together with vitriol (hydrated sulfates of various metals) produced hydrogen chloride.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] However, it appears that in these early experiments with chloride salts, the gaseous products were discarded, and hydrogen chloride may have been produced many times before it was discovered that it can be put to chemical use.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Another important development was the discovery by pseudo-Geber (in the *De inventione veritatis*, "On the Discovery of Truth", after c.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] 1300) that by adding ammonium chloride to nitric acid, a strong solvent capable of dissolving gold (i.e., *aqua regia*) could be produced.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Although *aqua regia* is an unstable mixture that continually gives off fumes containing free chlorine gas, this chlorine gas appears to have been ignored until c.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] 1630, when its nature as a separate gaseous substance was recognised by the Brabantian chemist and physician Jan Baptist van Helmont.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The element was first studied in detail in 1774 by Swedish chemist Carl Wilhelm Scheele, and he is credited with the discovery.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Scheele observed several of the properties of chlorine: the bleaching effect on litmus, the deadly effect on insects, the yellow-green colour, and the smell similar to aqua regia.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] He called it "*dephlogisticated muriatic acid air*" since it is a gas (then called "airs") and it came from hydrochloric acid (then known as "muriatic acid").
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] He failed to establish chlorine as an element.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In 1809, Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac and Louis-Jacques Thénard tried to decompose *dephlogisticated muriatic acid air* by reacting it with charcoal to release the free element *muriaticum* (and carbon dioxide).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] They did not succeed and published a report in which they considered the possibility that *dephlogisticated muriatic acid air* is an element, but were not convinced.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In 1810, Sir Humphry Davy tried the same experiment again, and concluded that the substance was an element, and not a compound.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] He announced his results to the Royal Society on 15 November that year.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] At that time, he named this new element "chlorine", from the Greek word χλωρος (*chlōros*, "green-yellow"), in reference to its colour.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The name "halogen", meaning "salt producer", was originally used for chlorine in 1811 by Johann Salomo Christoph Schweigger.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This term was later used as a generic term to describe all the elements in the chlorine family (fluorine, bromine, iodine), after a suggestion by Jöns Jakob Berzelius in 1826.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In 1823, Michael Faraday liquefied chlorine for the first time, and demonstrated that what was then known as "solid chlorine" had a structure of chlorine hydrate (Cl2·H2O).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine gas was first used by French chemist Claude Berthollet to bleach textiles in 1785.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Modern bleaches resulted from further work by Berthollet, who first produced sodium hypochlorite in 1789 in his laboratory in the town of Javel (now part of Paris, France), by passing chlorine gas through a solution of sodium carbonate.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The resulting liquid, known as "*Eau de Javel*" ("Javel water"), was a weak solution of sodium hypochlorite.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This process was not very efficient, and alternative production methods were sought.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Scottish chemist and industrialist Charles Tennant first produced a solution of calcium hypochlorite ("chlorinated lime"), then solid calcium hypochlorite (bleaching powder).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] These compounds produced low levels of elemental chlorine and could be more efficiently transported than sodium hypochlorite, which remained as dilute solutions because when purified to eliminate water, it became a dangerously powerful and unstable oxidiser.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Near the end of the nineteenth century, E.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Smith patented a method of sodium hypochlorite production involving electrolysis of brine to produce sodium hydroxide and chlorine gas, which then mixed to form sodium hypochlorite.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This is known as the chloralkali process, first introduced on an industrial scale in 1892, and now the source of most elemental chlorine and sodium hydroxide.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In 1884, the Chemische Fabrik Griesheim in Germany developed another chloralkali process which entered commercial production in 1888.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Elemental chlorine solutions dissolved in chemically basic water (sodium and calcium hypochlorite) were first used as anti-putrefaction agents and disinfectants in the 1820s, in France, long before the establishment of the germ theory of disease.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This practice was pioneered by Antoine-Germain Labarraque, who adapted Berthollet's "Javel water" bleach and other chlorine preparations.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Elemental chlorine has since served a continuous function in topical antisepsis (wound irrigation solutions and the like) and public sanitation, particularly in swimming and drinking water.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine gas was first used as a weapon on 22 April 1915 at the Second Battle of Ypres by the German Army.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The effect on the Allied forces was devastating because the existing gas masks were difficult to deploy and had not been broadly distributed.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine is the second halogen, being a nonmetal in group 17 of the periodic table.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Its properties are thus similar to fluorine, bromine, and iodine, and are largely intermediate between those of the first two.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine has the electron configuration [Ne]3s23p5, with the seven electrons in the third and outermost shell acting as its valence electrons.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Like all halogens, it is thus one electron short of a full octet, and is hence a strong oxidising agent, reacting with many elements in order to complete its outer shell.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Corresponding to periodic trends, it is intermediate in electronegativity between fluorine and bromine (F: 3.98, Cl: 3.16, Br: 2.96, I: 2.66), and is less reactive than fluorine and more reactive than bromine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is also a weaker oxidising agent than fluorine, but a stronger one than bromine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Conversely, the chloride ion is a weaker reducing agent than bromide, but a stronger one than fluoride.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] All four stable halogens experience intermolecular van der Waals forces of attraction, and their strength increases together with the number of electrons among all homonuclear diatomic halogen molecules.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Thus, the melting and boiling points of chlorine are intermediate between those of fluorine and bromine: chlorine melts at −101.0 °C and boils at −34.0 °C.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The halogens darken in colour as the group is descended: thus, while fluorine is a pale yellow gas, chlorine is distinctly yellow-green.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This trend occurs because the wavelengths of visible light absorbed by the halogens increase down the group.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Specifically, the colour of a halogen, such as chlorine, results from the electron transition between the highest occupied antibonding *πg* molecular orbital and the lowest vacant antibonding *σu* molecular orbital.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The colour fades at low temperatures, so that solid chlorine at −195 °C is almost colourless.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Like solid bromine and iodine, solid chlorine crystallises in the orthorhombic crystal system, in a layered lattice of Cl2 molecules.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The Cl–Cl distance is 198 pm (close to the gaseous Cl–Cl distance of 199 pm) and the Cl···Cl distance between molecules is 332 pm within a layer and 382 pm between layers (compare the van der Waals radius of chlorine, 180 pm).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This structure means that chlorine is a very poor conductor of electricity, and indeed its conductivity is so low as to be practically unmeasurable.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine has two stable isotopes, 35Cl and 37Cl.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] These are its only two natural isotopes occurring in quantity, with 35Cl making up 76% of natural chlorine and 37Cl making up the remaining 24%.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Both are synthesised in stars in the oxygen-burning and silicon-burning processes.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The other chlorine isotopes are all radioactive, with half-lives too short to occur in nature primordially.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Of these, the most commonly used in the laboratory are 36Cl (*t*1/2 = 3.0×105 y) and 38Cl (*t*1/2 = 37.2 min), which may be produced from the neutron activation of natural chlorine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The most stable chlorine radioisotope is 36Cl.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The primary decay mode of isotopes lighter than 35Cl is electron capture to isotopes of sulfur; that of isotopes heavier than 37Cl is beta decay to isotopes of argon; and 36Cl may decay by either mode to stable 36S or 36Ar.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] 36Cl occurs in trace quantities in nature as a cosmogenic nuclide in a ratio of about (7–10) × 10−13 to 1 with stable chlorine isotopes: it is produced in the atmosphere by spallation of 36Ar by interactions with cosmic ray protons.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In the top meter of the lithosphere, 36Cl is generated primarily by thermal neutron activation of 35Cl and spallation of 39K and 40Ca.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In the subsurface environment, muon capture by 40Ca becomes more important as a way to generate 36Cl.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine is intermediate in reactivity between fluorine and bromine, and is one of the most reactive elements.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine is a weaker oxidising agent than fluorine but a stronger one than bromine or iodine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This can be seen from the standard electrode potentials of the X2/X− couples (F, +2.866 V; Cl, +1.395 V; Br, +1.087 V; I, +0.615 V; At, approximately +0.3 V).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] However, this trend is not shown in the bond energies because fluorine is singular due to its small size, low polarisability, and inability to show hypervalence.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] As another difference, chlorine has a significant chemistry in positive oxidation states while fluorine does not.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorination often leads to higher oxidation states than bromination or iodination but lower oxidation states than fluorination.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine tends to react with compounds including M–M, M–H, or M–C bonds to form M–Cl bonds.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Given that E°(⁠1/2⁠O2/H2O) = +1.229 V, which is less than +1.395 V, it would be expected that chlorine should be able to oxidise water to oxygen and hydrochloric acid.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] However, the kinetics of this reaction are unfavourable, and there is also a bubble overpotential effect to consider, so that electrolysis of aqueous chloride solutions evolves chlorine gas and not oxygen gas, a fact that is very useful for the industrial production of chlorine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The simplest chlorine compound is hydrogen chloride, HCl, a major chemical in industry as well as in the laboratory, both as a gas and dissolved in water as hydrochloric acid.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is often produced by burning hydrogen gas in chlorine gas, or as a byproduct of chlorinating hydrocarbons.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In the laboratory, hydrogen chloride gas may be made by drying the a concentrated aqueous solution of acid with concentrated sulfuric acid.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Deuterium chloride, DCl, may be produced by reacting benzoyl chloride with heavy water (D2O).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Hydrochloric acid is a strong acid (p*K*a = −7) because the hydrogen-chlorine bonds are too weak to inhibit dissociation.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The HCl/H2O system has many hydrates HCl·*n*H2O for *n* = 1, 2, 3, 4, and 6.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Beyond a 1:1 mixture of HCl and H2O, the system separates completely into two separate liquid phases.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Hydrochloric acid forms an azeotrope with boiling point 108.58 °C at 20.22 g HCl per 100 g solution; thus hydrochloric acid cannot be concentrated beyond this point by distillation.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Anhydrous hydrogen chloride is a poor solvent, only able to dissolve small molecular compounds such as nitrosyl chloride and phenol, or salts with very low lattice energies such as tetraalkylammonium halides.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It readily protonates nucleophiles containing lone-pairs or π bonds.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Nearly all elements in the periodic table form binary chlorides.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Even though nitrogen in NCl3 is bearing a negative charge, the compound is usually called nitrogen trichloride.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorination of metals with Cl2 usually leads to a higher oxidation state than bromination with Br2 when multiple oxidation states are available, such as in MoCl5 and MoBr3.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorides can be made by reaction of an element or its oxide, hydroxide, or carbonate with hydrochloric acid, and then dehydrated by mildly high temperatures combined with either low pressure or anhydrous hydrogen chloride gas.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] For instance, zirconium dioxide reacts with chlorine at standard conditions to produce zirconium tetrachloride, and uranium trioxide reacts with hexachloropropene when heated under reflux to give uranium tetrachloride.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The second example also involves a reduction in oxidation state, which can also be achieved by reducing a higher chloride using hydrogen or a metal as a reducing agent.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Most metal chlorides with the metal in low oxidation states (+1 to +3) are ionic.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Nonmetals tend to form covalent molecular chlorides, as do metals in high oxidation states from +3 and above.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Both ionic and covalent chlorides are known for metals in oxidation state +3 (e.g. scandium chloride is mostly ionic, but aluminium chloride is not).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Silver chloride is very insoluble in water and is thus often used as a qualitative test for chlorine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Although dichlorine is a strong oxidising agent with a high first ionisation energy, it may be oxidised under extreme conditions to form the [Cl2]+ cation.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This is very unstable and has only been characterised by its electronic band spectrum when produced in a low-pressure discharge tube.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This reaction is conducted in the oxidising solvent arsenic pentafluoride.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The trichloride anion, [Cl3]−, has also been characterised; it is analogous to triiodide.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This cation was characterized by X-ray diffraction as being rectangular in geometry (194 pm Cl–Cl and 294 pm Cl···Cl), consisting of two Cl2 units bonded by π*–π* orbital interactions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Despite the long bond length between the two Cl2 units, dissociation to Cl2 + Cl+2 was found to be endothermic by approximately 25 kcal/mol.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It reacts with O2 to give a complex containing the [Cl2O2]+ cation.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The three fluorides of chlorine form a subset of the interhalogen compounds, all of which are diamagnetic.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Some cationic and anionic derivatives are known, such as ClF− 2, ClF− 4, ClF+ 2, and Cl2F+.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Some pseudohalides of chlorine are also known, such as cyanogen chloride (ClCN, linear), chlorine cyanate (ClNCO), chlorine thiocyanate (ClSCN, unlike its oxygen counterpart), and chlorine azide (ClN3).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine monofluoride (ClF) is extremely thermally stable, and is sold commercially in 500-gram steel lecture bottles.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is a colourless gas that melts at −155.6 °C and boils at −100.1 °C.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It may be produced by the reaction of its elements at 225 °C, though it must then be separated and purified from chlorine trifluoride and its reactants.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Its properties are mostly intermediate between those of chlorine and fluorine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It will react with many metals and nonmetals from room temperature and above, fluorinating them and liberating chlorine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It will also act as a chlorofluorinating agent, adding chlorine and fluorine across a multiple bond or by oxidation: for example, it will attack carbon monoxide to form carbonyl chlorofluoride, COFCl.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It will react analogously with hexafluoroacetone, (CF3)2CO, with a potassium fluoride catalyst to produce heptafluoroisopropyl hypochlorite, (CF3)2CFOCl; with nitriles RCN to produce RCF2NCl2; and with the sulfur oxides SO2 and SO3 to produce ClSO2F and ClOSO2F respectively.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine trifluoride (ClF3) is a volatile colourless molecular liquid which melts at −76.3 °C and boils at 11.8 °C.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It may be formed by directly fluorinating gaseous chlorine or chlorine monofluoride at 200–300 °C.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] One of the most reactive chemical compounds known, the list of elements it sets on fire is diverse, containing hydrogen, potassium, phosphorus, arsenic, antimony, sulfur, selenium, tellurium, bromine, iodine, and powdered molybdenum, tungsten, rhodium, iridium, and iron.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It will also ignite water, along with many substances which in ordinary circumstances would be considered chemically inert such as asbestos, concrete, glass, and sand.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] When heated, it will even corrode noble metals as palladium, platinum, and gold, and even the noble gases xenon and radon do not escape fluorination.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] An impermeable fluoride layer is formed by sodium, magnesium, aluminium, zinc, tin, and silver, which may be removed by heating.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Nickel, copper, and steel containers are usually used due to their great resistance to attack by chlorine trifluoride, stemming from the formation of an unreactive layer of metal fluoride.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Its reaction with hydrazine to form hydrogen fluoride, nitrogen, and chlorine gases was used in experimental rocket engine, but has problems largely stemming from its extreme hypergolicity resulting in ignition without any measurable delay.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Today, it is mostly used in nuclear fuel processing, to oxidise uranium to uranium hexafluoride for its enriching and to separate it from plutonium, as well as in the semiconductor industry, where it is used to clean chemical vapour deposition chambers.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It can act as a fluoride ion donor or acceptor (Lewis base or acid), although it does not dissociate appreciably into ClF+ 2 and ClF− 4 ions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine pentafluoride (ClF5) is made on a large scale by direct fluorination of chlorine with excess fluorine gas at 350 °C and 250 atm, and on a small scale by reacting metal chlorides with fluorine gas at 100–300 °C.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is a very strong fluorinating agent, although it is still not as effective as chlorine trifluoride.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Only a few specific stoichiometric reactions have been characterised.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The product, chloryl fluoride, is one of the five known chlorine oxide fluorides.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] These range from the thermally unstable FClO to the chemically unreactive perchloryl fluoride (FClO3), the other three being FClO2, F3ClO, and F3ClO2.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] All five behave similarly to the chlorine fluorides, both structurally and chemically, and may act as Lewis acids or bases by gaining or losing fluoride ions respectively or as very strong oxidising and fluorinating agents.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The chlorine oxides are well-studied in spite of their instability (all of them are endothermic compounds).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] They are important because they are produced when chlorofluorocarbons undergo photolysis in the upper atmosphere and cause the destruction of the ozone layer.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] None of them can be made from directly reacting the elements.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Dichlorine monoxide (Cl2O) is a brownish-yellow gas (red-brown when solid or liquid) which may be obtained by reacting chlorine gas with yellow mercury(II) oxide.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is very soluble in water, in which it is in equilibrium with hypochlorous acid (HOCl), of which it is the anhydride.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is thus an effective bleach and is mostly used to make hypochlorites.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It explodes on heating or sparking or in the presence of ammonia gas.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine dioxide (ClO2) was the first chlorine oxide to be discovered in 1811 by Humphry Davy.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is a yellow paramagnetic gas (deep-red as a solid or liquid), as expected from its having an odd number of electrons: it is stable towards dimerisation due to the delocalisation of the unpaired electron.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It explodes above −40 °C as a liquid and under pressure as a gas and therefore must be made at low concentrations for wood-pulp bleaching and water treatment.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Its production is thus intimately linked to the redox reactions of the chlorine oxoacids.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is a strong oxidising agent, reacting with sulfur, phosphorus, phosphorus halides, and potassium borohydride.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It dissolves exothermically in water to form dark-green solutions that very slowly decompose in the dark.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Crystalline clathrate hydrates ClO2·*n*H2O (*n* ≈ 6–10) separate at low temperatures.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] However, in the presence of light, these solutions rapidly photodecompose to form a mixture of chloric and hydrochloric acids.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Photolysis of individual ClO2 molecules result in the radicals ClO and ClOO, while at room temperature mostly chlorine, oxygen, and some ClO3 and Cl2O6 are produced.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Cl2O3 is also produced when photolysing the solid at −78 °C: it is a dark brown solid that explodes below 0 °C.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine perchlorate (ClOClO3) is a pale yellow liquid that is less stable than ClO2 and decomposes at room temperature to form chlorine, oxygen, and dichlorine hexoxide (Cl2O6).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Dichlorine hexoxide is a dark-red liquid that freezes to form a solid which turns yellow at −180 °C: it is usually made by reaction of chlorine dioxide with oxygen.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Despite attempts to rationalise it as the dimer of ClO3, it reacts more as though it were chloryl perchlorate, [ClO2]+[ClO4]−, which has been confirmed to be the correct structure of the solid.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It hydrolyses in water to give a mixture of chloric and perchloric acids: the analogous reaction with anhydrous hydrogen fluoride does not proceed to completion.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Dichlorine heptoxide (Cl2O7) is the anhydride of perchloric acid (HClO4) and can readily be obtained from it by dehydrating it with phosphoric acid at −10 °C and then distilling the product at −35 °C and 1 mmHg.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is a shock-sensitive, colourless oily liquid.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is the least reactive of the chlorine oxides, being the only one to not set organic materials on fire at room temperature.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It may be dissolved in water to regenerate perchloric acid or in aqueous alkalis to regenerate perchlorates.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] However, it thermally decomposes explosively by breaking one of the central Cl–O bonds, producing the radicals ClO3 and ClO4 which immediately decompose to the elements through intermediate oxides.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine forms four oxoacids: hypochlorous acid (HOCl), chlorous acid (HOClO), chloric acid (HOClO2), and perchloric acid (HOClO3).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The hypochlorite ions also disproportionate further to produce chloride and chlorate (3 ClO− ⇌ 2 Cl− + ClO− 3) but this reaction is quite slow at temperatures below 70 °C in spite of the very favourable equilibrium constant of 1027.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The chlorate ions may themselves disproportionate to form chloride and perchlorate (4 ClO− 3 ⇌ Cl− + 3 ClO− 4) but this is still very slow even at 100 °C despite the very favourable equilibrium constant of 1020.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The rates of reaction for the chlorine oxyanions increases as the oxidation state of chlorine decreases.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The strengths of the chlorine oxyacids increase very quickly as the oxidation state of chlorine increases due to the increasing delocalisation of charge over more and more oxygen atoms in their conjugate bases.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Most of the chlorine oxoacids may be produced by exploiting these disproportionation reactions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Hypochlorous acid (HOCl) is highly reactive and quite unstable; its salts are mostly used for their bleaching and sterilising abilities.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] They are very strong oxidising agents, transferring an oxygen atom to most inorganic species.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorous acid (HOClO) is even more unstable and cannot be isolated or concentrated without decomposition: it is known from the decomposition of aqueous chlorine dioxide.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] However, sodium chlorite is a stable salt and is useful for bleaching and stripping textiles, as an oxidising agent, and as a source of chlorine dioxide.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chloric acid (HOClO2) is a strong acid that is quite stable in cold water up to 30% concentration, but on warming gives chlorine and chlorine dioxide.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Evaporation under reduced pressure allows it to be concentrated further to about 40%, but then it decomposes to perchloric acid, chlorine, oxygen, water, and chlorine dioxide.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Its most important salt is sodium chlorate, mostly used to make chlorine dioxide to bleach paper pulp.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The decomposition of chlorate to chloride and oxygen is a common way to produce oxygen in the laboratory on a small scale.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Perchlorates and perchloric acid (HOClO3) are the most stable oxo-compounds of chlorine, in keeping with the fact that chlorine compounds are most stable when the chlorine atom is in its lowest (−1) or highest (+7) possible oxidation states.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Perchloric acid and aqueous perchlorates are vigorous and sometimes violent oxidising agents when heated, in stark contrast to their mostly inactive nature at room temperature due to the high activation energies for these reactions for kinetic reasons.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Perchlorates are made by electrolytically oxidising sodium chlorate, and perchloric acid is made by reacting anhydrous sodium perchlorate or barium perchlorate with concentrated hydrochloric acid, filtering away the chloride precipitated and distilling the filtrate to concentrate it.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Anhydrous perchloric acid is a colourless mobile liquid that is sensitive to shock that explodes on contact with most organic compounds, sets hydrogen iodide and thionyl chloride on fire and even oxidises silver and gold.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Although it is a weak ligand, weaker than water, a few compounds involving coordinated ClO− 4 are known.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The Table below presents typical oxidation states for chlorine element as given in the secondary schools or colleges.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] There are more complex chemical compounds, the structure of which can only be explained using modern quantum chemical methods, for example, cluster technetium chloride [(CH3)4N]3[Tc6Cl14], in which 6 of the 14 chlorine atoms are formally divalent, and oxidation states are fractional.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In addition, all the above chemical regularities are valid for "normal" or close to normal conditions, while at ultra-high pressures (for example, in the cores of large planets), chlorine can form a Na3Cl compound with sodium, which does not fit into traditional concepts of chemistry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Like the other carbon–halogen bonds, the C–Cl bond is a common functional group that forms part of core organic chemistry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Formally, compounds with this functional group may be considered organic derivatives of the chloride anion.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Due to the difference of electronegativity between chlorine (3.16) and carbon (2.55), the carbon in a C–Cl bond is electron-deficient and thus electrophilic.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorination modifies the physical properties of hydrocarbons in several ways: chlorocarbons are typically denser than water due to the higher atomic weight of chlorine versus hydrogen, and aliphatic organochlorides are alkylating agents because chloride is a leaving group.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Alkanes and aryl alkanes may be chlorinated under free-radical conditions, with UV light.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] However, the extent of chlorination is difficult to control: the reaction is not regioselective and often results in a mixture of various isomers with different degrees of chlorination, though this may be permissible if the products are easily separated.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Aryl chlorides may be prepared by the Friedel-Crafts halogenation, using chlorine and a Lewis acid catalyst.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The haloform reaction, using chlorine and sodium hydroxide, is also able to generate alkyl halides from methyl ketones, and related compounds.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine adds to the multiple bonds on alkenes and alkynes as well, giving di- or tetrachloro compounds.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] However, due to the expense and reactivity of chlorine, organochlorine compounds are more commonly produced by using hydrogen chloride, or with chlorinating agents such as phosphorus pentachloride (PCl5) or thionyl chloride (SOCl2).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The last is very convenient in the laboratory because all side products are gaseous and do not have to be distilled out.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Many organochlorine compounds have been isolated from natural sources ranging from bacteria to humans.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorinated organic compounds are found in nearly every class of biomolecules including alkaloids, terpenes, amino acids, flavonoids, steroids, and fatty acids.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Organochlorides, including dioxins, are produced in the high temperature environment of forest fires, and dioxins have been found in the preserved ashes of lightning-ignited fires that predate synthetic dioxins.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In addition, a variety of simple chlorinated hydrocarbons including dichloromethane, chloroform, and carbon tetrachloride have been isolated from marine algae.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] A majority of the chloromethane in the environment is produced naturally by biological decomposition, forest fires, and volcanoes.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Some types of organochlorides, though not all, have significant toxicity to plants or animals, including humans.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Dioxins, produced when organic matter is burned in the presence of chlorine, and some insecticides, such as DDT, are persistent organic pollutants which pose dangers when they are released into the environment.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] For example, DDT, which was widely used to control insects in the mid 20th century, also accumulates in food chains, and causes reproductive problems (e.g., eggshell thinning) in certain bird species.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Due to the ready homolytic fission of the C–Cl bond to create chlorine radicals in the upper atmosphere, chlorofluorocarbons have been discontinued due to the harm they do to the ozone layer.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine is too reactive to occur as the free element in nature but is very abundant in the form of its chloride salts.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] It is the 20th most abundant element in Earth's crust and makes up 126 parts per million of it, through the large deposits of chloride minerals, especially sodium chloride, that have been evaporated from water bodies.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] All of these pale in comparison to the reserves of chloride ions in seawater: smaller amounts at higher concentrations occur in some inland seas and underground brine wells, such as the Great Salt Lake in Utah and the Dead Sea in Israel.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Small batches of chlorine gas are prepared in the laboratory by combining hydrochloric acid and manganese dioxide, but the need rarely arises due to its ready availability.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In industry, elemental chlorine is usually produced by the electrolysis of sodium chloride dissolved in water.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This method, the chloralkali process industrialised in 1892, now provides most industrial chlorine gas.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Along with chlorine, the method yields hydrogen gas and sodium hydroxide, which is the most valuable product.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Chlorine is primarily produced by the chloralkali process, although non-chloralkali processes exist.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Global 2022 production was estimated to be 97 million tonnes.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The most visible use of chlorine is in water disinfection.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] 35–40 % of chlorine produced is used to make poly(vinyl chloride) through ethylene dichloride and vinyl chloride.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The chlorine produced is available in cylinders from sizes ranging from 450 g to 70 kg, as well as drums (865 kg), tank wagons (15 tonnes on roads; 27–90 tonnes by rail), and barges (600–1200 tonnes).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Due to the difficulty and hazards in transporting elemental chlorine, production is typically located near where it is consumed.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] As examples, vinyl chloride producers such as Westlake Chemical and Formosa Plastics have integrated chloralkali assets.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In the conventional case where sodium chloride is electrolysed, sodium hydroxide and chlorine are coproducts.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The Castner–Kellner process was the first method used at the end of the nineteenth century to produce chlorine on an industrial scale.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Mercury (that is toxic) was used as an electrode to amalgamate the sodium product, preventing undesirable side reactions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In diaphragm cell electrolysis, an asbestos (or polymer-fibre) diaphragm separates a cathode and an anode, preventing the chlorine forming at the anode from re-mixing with the sodium hydroxide and the hydrogen formed at the cathode.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] The salt solution (brine) is continuously fed to the anode compartment and flows through the diaphragm to the cathode compartment, where the caustic alkali is produced and the brine is partially depleted.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Diaphragm methods produce dilute and slightly impure alkali, but they are not burdened with the problem of mercury disposal and they are more energy efficient.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Membrane cell electrolysis employs permeable membrane as an ion exchanger.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Saturated sodium (or potassium) chloride solution is passed through the anode compartment, leaving at a lower concentration.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] This method also produces very pure sodium (or potassium) hydroxide but has the disadvantage of requiring very pure brine at high concentrations.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] However, due to the lower energy requirements of the membrane process, new chlor-alkali installations are now almost exclusively employing the membrane process.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Next to this, the use of large volumes of mercury is considered undesirable.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Also, older plants are converted into the membrane process.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] In the Deacon process, hydrogen chloride recovered from the production of organochlorine compounds is recovered as chlorine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] As introduced by Deacon, early catalysts were based on copper.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p01] Commercial processes, such as the Mitsui MT-Chlorine Process, have switched to chromium and ruthenium-based catalysts.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Sodium chloride is the most common chlorine compound, and is the main source of chlorine for the demand by the chemical industry.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Quantitatively, of all elemental chlorine produced, about 63% is used in the manufacture of organic compounds, and 18% in the manufacture of inorganic chlorine compounds.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] About 15,000 chlorine compounds are used commercially.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The remaining 19% of chlorine produced is used for bleaches and disinfection products.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The most significant of organic compounds in terms of production volume are 1,2-dichloroethane and vinyl chloride, intermediates in the production of PVC.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Other particularly important organochlorines are methyl chloride, methylene chloride, chloroform, vinylidene chloride, trichloroethylene, perchloroethylene, allyl chloride, epichlorohydrin, chlorobenzene, dichlorobenzenes, and trichlorobenzenes.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The major inorganic compounds include HCl, Cl2O, HOCl, NaClO3, AlCl3, SiCl4, SnCl4, PCl3, PCl5, POCl3, AsCl3, SbCl3, SbCl5, BiCl3, and ZnCl2.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] In France (as elsewhere), animal intestines were processed to make musical instrument strings, Goldbeater's skin and other products.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] This was done in "gut factories" (*boyauderies*), and it was an odiferous and unhealthy process.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] In or about 1820, the Société d'encouragement pour l'industrie nationale offered a prize for the discovery of a method, chemical or mechanical, for separating the peritoneal membrane of animal intestines without putrefaction.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] They were successful in hospitals, lazarets, prisons, infirmaries (both on land and at sea), magnaneries, stables, cattle-sheds, etc.; and they were beneficial during exhumations, embalming, outbreaks of epidemic disease, fever, and blackleg in cattle.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Labarraque's chlorinated lime and soda solutions have been advocated since 1828 to prevent infection (called "contagious infection", presumed to be transmitted by "miasmas"), and to treat putrefaction of existing wounds, including septic wounds.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] In his 1828 work, Labarraque recommended that doctors breathe chlorine, wash their hands in chlorinated lime, and even sprinkle chlorinated lime about the patients' beds in cases of "contagious infection".
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] In 1828, the contagion of infections was well known, even though the agency of the microbe was not discovered until more than half a century later.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] During the Paris cholera outbreak of 1832, large quantities of so-called *chloride of lime* were used to disinfect the capital.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] This was not simply modern calcium chloride, but chlorine gas dissolved in lime-water (dilute calcium hydroxide) to form calcium hypochlorite (chlorinated lime).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Labarraque's discovery helped to remove the terrible stench of decay from hospitals and dissecting rooms, and by doing so, effectively deodorised the Latin Quarter of Paris.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] These "putrid miasmas" were thought by many to cause the spread of "contagion" and "infection" – both words used before the germ theory of infection.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chloride of lime was used for destroying odors and "putrid matter".
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] One source claims chloride of lime was used by Dr.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] John Snow to disinfect water from the cholera-contaminated well that was feeding the Broad Street pump in 1854 London, though three other reputable sources that describe that famous cholera epidemic do not mention the incident.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] One reference makes it clear that chloride of lime was used to disinfect the offal and filth in the streets surrounding the Broad Street pump – a common practice in mid-nineteenth century England.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Much later, during World War I in 1916, a standardised and diluted modification of Labarraque's solution containing hypochlorite (0.5%) and boric acid as an acidic stabiliser was developed by Henry Drysdale Dakin (who gave full credit to Labarraque's prior work in this area).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Called Dakin's solution, the method of wound irrigation with chlorinated solutions allowed antiseptic treatment of a wide variety of open wounds, long before the modern antibiotic era.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] A modified version of this solution continues to be employed in wound irrigation in modern times, where it remains effective against bacteria that are resistant to multiple antibiotics.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The first continuous application of chlorination to drinking U.S. water was installed in Jersey City, New Jersey, in 1908.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] By 1918, the US Department of Treasury called for all drinking water to be disinfected with chlorine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chlorine is presently an important chemical for water purification (such as in water treatment plants), in disinfectants, and in bleach.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Even small water supplies are now routinely chlorinated.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chlorine is usually used (in the form of hypochlorous acid) to kill bacteria and other microbes in drinking water supplies and public swimming pools.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] In most private swimming pools, chlorine itself is not used, but rather sodium hypochlorite, formed from chlorine and sodium hydroxide, or solid tablets of chlorinated isocyanurates.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The drawback of using chlorine in swimming pools is that the chlorine reacts with the amino acids in proteins in human hair and skin.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Contrary to popular belief, the distinctive "chlorine aroma" associated with swimming pools is not the result of elemental chlorine itself, but of chloramine, a chemical compound produced by the reaction of free dissolved chlorine with amines in organic substances including those in urine and sweat.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] As a disinfectant in water, chlorine is more than three times as effective against *Escherichia coli* as bromine, and more than six times as effective as iodine.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Increasingly, monochloramine itself is being directly added to drinking water for purposes of disinfection, a process known as chloramination.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] It is often impractical to store and use poisonous chlorine gas for water treatment, so alternative methods of adding chlorine are used.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] These include hypochlorite solutions, which gradually release chlorine into the water, and compounds like sodium dichloro-s-triazinetrione (dihydrate or anhydrous), sometimes referred to as "dichlor", and trichloro-s-triazinetrione, sometimes referred to as "trichlor".
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] These compounds are stable while solid and may be used in powdered, granular, or tablet form.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] When added in small amounts to pool water or industrial water systems, the chlorine atoms hydrolyse from the rest of the molecule, forming hypochlorous acid (HOCl), which acts as a general biocide, killing germs, microorganisms, algae, and so on.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chlorine gas, also known as bertholite, was first used as a weapon in World War I by Germany on 22 April 1915, in the Second Battle of Ypres.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] As described by the soldiers, it had the distinctive smell of a mixture of pepper and pineapple.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] It also tasted metallic and stung the back of the throat and chest.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chlorine reacts with water in the mucosa of the lungs to form hydrochloric acid, destructive to living tissue and potentially lethal.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Human respiratory systems can be protected from chlorine gas by gas masks with activated charcoal or other filters, which makes chlorine gas much less lethal than other chemical weapons.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] It was pioneered by a German scientist later to be a Nobel laureate, Fritz Haber of the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Berlin, in collaboration with the German chemical conglomerate IG Farben, which developed methods for discharging chlorine gas against an entrenched enemy.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] After its first use, both sides in the conflict used chlorine as a chemical weapon, but it was soon replaced by the more deadly phosgene and more debilitating mustard gas.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chlorine gas was also used during the Iraq War in Anbar Province in 2007, with insurgents packing truck bombs with mortar shells and chlorine tanks.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The attacks killed two people from the explosives and sickened more than 350.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Most of the deaths were caused by the force of the explosions rather than the effects of chlorine since the toxic gas is readily dispersed and diluted in the atmosphere by the blast.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] In some bombings, over a hundred civilians were hospitalised due to breathing difficulties.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The Iraqi authorities tightened security for elemental chlorine, which is essential for providing safe drinking water to the population.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] On 23 October 2014, it was reported that the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant had used chlorine gas in the town of Duluiyah, Iraq.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Laboratory analysis of clothing and soil samples confirmed the use of chlorine gas against Kurdish Peshmerga Forces in a vehicle-borne improvised explosive device attack on 23 January 2015 at the Highway 47 Kiske Junction near Mosul.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Another country in the Middle East, Syria, has used chlorine as a chemical weapon delivered from barrel bombs and rockets.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] In 2016, the OPCW-UN Joint Investigative Mechanism concluded that the Syrian government used chlorine as a chemical weapon in three separate attacks.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Later investigations from the OPCW's Investigation and Identification Team concluded that the Syrian Air Force was responsible for chlorine attacks in 2017 and 2018.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The chloride anion is an essential nutrient for metabolism.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chlorine is needed for the production of hydrochloric acid in the stomach and in cellular pump functions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The main dietary source is table salt, or sodium chloride.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Overly low or high concentrations of chloride in the blood are examples of electrolyte disturbances.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Hypochloremia (having too little chloride) rarely occurs in the absence of other abnormalities.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] It is sometimes associated with hypoventilation.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] It can be associated with chronic respiratory acidosis.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Hyperchloremia (having too much chloride) usually does not produce symptoms.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] When symptoms do occur, they tend to resemble those of hypernatremia (having too much sodium).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Reduction in blood chloride leads to cerebral dehydration; symptoms are most often caused by rapid rehydration which results in cerebral edema.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Hyperchloremia can affect oxygen transport.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chlorine is a toxic gas that attacks the respiratory system, eyes, and skin.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Because it is denser than air, it tends to accumulate at the bottom of poorly ventilated spaces.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chlorine gas is a strong oxidiser, which may react with flammable materials.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chlorine is detectable with measuring devices in concentrations as low as 0.2 parts per million (ppm), and by smell at 3 ppm.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Coughing and vomiting may occur at 30 ppm and lung damage at 60 ppm.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] About 1000 ppm can be fatal after a few deep breaths of the gas.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The IDLH (immediately dangerous to life and health) concentration is 10 ppm.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Breathing lower concentrations can aggravate the respiratory system and exposure to the gas can irritate the eyes.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] When chlorine is inhaled at concentrations greater than 30 ppm, it reacts with water within the lungs, producing hydrochloric acid (HCl) and hypochlorous acid (HOCl).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] When used at specified levels for water disinfection, the reaction of chlorine with water is not a major concern for human health.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Other materials present in the water may generate disinfection by-products that are associated with negative effects on human health.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] In the United States, the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has set the permissible exposure limit for elemental chlorine at 1 ppm, or 3 mg/m3.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health has designated a recommended exposure limit of 0.5 ppm over 15 minutes.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] In the home, accidents occur when hypochlorite bleach solutions come into contact with certain acidic drain-cleaners to produce chlorine gas.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Hypochlorite bleach (a popular laundry additive) combined with ammonia (another popular laundry additive) produces chloramines, another toxic group of chemicals.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chlorine is widely used for purifying water, especially potable water supplies and water used in swimming pools.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Several catastrophic collapses of swimming pool ceilings have occurred from chlorine-induced stress corrosion cracking of stainless steel suspension rods.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Some polymers are also sensitive to attack, including acetal resin and polybutene.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Both materials were used in hot and cold water domestic plumbing, and stress corrosion cracking caused widespread failures in the US in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] The element iron can combine with chlorine at high temperatures in a strong exothermic reaction, creating a *chlorine–iron fire*.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/chlorine-p02] Chlorine–iron fires are a risk in chemical process plants, where much of the pipework that carries chlorine gas is made of steel.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] As of 2022, the college had 661 students.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Its grounds contain a number of architecturally significant buildings including Tom Tower (designed by Sir Christopher Wren), Tom Quad (the largest quadrangle in Oxford), and the Great Dining Hall, which was the seat of the parliament assembled by King Charles I during the English Civil War.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college's alumni include 13 British prime ministers (the highest number of any Oxbridge college), as well as former prime ministers of Pakistan and Ceylon.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Other notable alumni include King Edward VII, King William II of the Netherlands, William Penn, writers Lewis Carroll (author of *Alice in Wonderland*) and W.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Auden, philosopher John Locke, and scientist Robert Hooke.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Two Nobel laureates, Martin Ryle and John Gurdon, studied at Christ Church.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Albert Einstein is also associated with the college.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college has several cities and places named after it.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] He planned the establishment on a magnificent scale, but fell from grace in 1529, with the buildings only three-quarters complete, as they were to remain for 140 years.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] In 1531 the college was itself suppressed, but it was refounded in 1532 as **King Henry VIII's College** by Henry VIII, to whom Wolsey's property had escheated.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Then in 1546 the King, who had broken from the Catholic Church and acquired great wealth through the dissolution of the monasteries in England, refounded the college as **Christ Church** as part of the reorganisation of the Church of England.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The former priory church was made both the cathedral of the recently created Diocese of Oxford, and the chapel of the new college.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Christ Church's sister college in the University of Cambridge is Trinity College, Cambridge, founded the same year by Henry VIII.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Since the time of Queen Elizabeth I the college has also been associated with Westminster School.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The dean remains to this day an *ex officio* member of the school's governing body.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Major additions have been made to the buildings through the centuries, and Wolsey's Great Quadrangle was crowned with the famous gate-tower designed by Christopher Wren.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] To this day, the bell in the tower, Great Tom, is rung 101 times at 9 pm measured by Oxford time, meaning at 9:05 pm GMT/BST every night, once for each of the 100 original scholars of the college, plus one more stroke added in 1664.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] In former times this was done at midnight, signalling the close of all college gates throughout Oxford.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Since it took 20 minutes to ring the 101, the Christ Church gates, unlike those of other colleges, did not close until 12:20 am.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] When the ringing was moved back to 9:00 pm, Christ Church gates still remained open until 12.20, 20 minutes later than any other college.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Although the clock itself now shows GMT/BST, Christ Church still follows Oxford time in the timings of services in the cathedral.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] King Charles I made the Deanery his palace and held his Parliament in the Great Hall during the English Civil War.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] In the evening of 29 May 1645, during the second siege of Oxford, a "bullet of IX lb. weight" shot from the Parliamentarians' warning-piece at Marston fell against the wall of the north side of the Hall.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Several of Christ Church's deans achieved high academic distinction, notably Owen under the Commonwealth, Aldrich and Fell in the Restoration period, Jackson and Gaisford in the early 19th century and Liddell in the high Victorian era.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] For more than four centuries Christ Church admitted men only; the first female students at Christ Church matriculated in 1980.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Christ Church, formally titled "The Dean and Chapter of the Cathedral Church of Christ in Oxford of the Foundation of King Henry the Eighth", is the only academic institution in the world which is also a cathedral, the seat (cathedra) of the Bishop of Oxford.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The visitor of Christ Church is the reigning British sovereign (currently King Charles III), and the Bishop of Oxford is unique among English bishops in not being the visitor of his own cathedral.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The head of the college is the Dean of Christ Church.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Christ Church is unique among Oxford colleges in that its head of house, who is head of both college and cathedral, must be an Anglican cleric appointed by the Crown as dean of the cathedral church.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The dean lives on site in a grand 16th-century house in the main quadrangle.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college's activities are managed by a senior and a junior censor (formally titled the *Censor Moralis Philosophiae* and the *Censor Naturalis Philosophiae*) the former of whom is responsible for academic matters, the latter for undergraduate discipline.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] They are chosen from among the members of the governing body.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] A *censor theologiae* is also appointed to act as the dean's deputy.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college is always referred to as simply "Christ Church", and never "Christ Church College".
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college's own statutes refer to the institution as either "Christ Church" or "the House".
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The governing body of Christ Church consists of the dean and chapter of the cathedral, together with the "Students of Christ Church", who are not junior members but rather the equivalent of the fellows of the other colleges.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Until the later 19th century, the students differed from fellows in that they had no governing powers in their own college, as those resided solely with the dean and chapter.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The governing body of Christ Church now has around 60 members.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Serving alongside the seven members of chapter, the other members include statutory professors and associate professors with joint appointments (employed both by the University and Christ Church) as well as early-career career development fellows on fixed-term contracts.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Sir John Bell and Sir Tim Berners-Lee are both members of the governing body of Christ Church.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Christ Church sits in approximately 175 acres (71 hectares) of land.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] This includes the Christ Church Meadow (including Merton Field and Boathouse Island), which is open to the public all year round.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] In addition Christ Church own Aston's Eyot (purchased from All Souls College in 1891), Christ Church recreation ground (including the site of Liddell Building), and School Field which has been leased to Magdalen College School since 1893.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The meadow itself is inhabited by English Longhorn cattle.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] In October 1783 James Sadler made the first hot air balloon ascent in Britain from the meadow.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college gardens, quadrangles, and meadow are Grade I listed on the Register of Historic Parks and Gardens.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Christ Church has a number of architecturally significant buildings.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college buildings and grounds are the setting for parts of Evelyn Waugh's *Brideshead Revisited*, as well as a small part of Lewis Carroll's *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland*.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] More recently it has been used in the filming of the movies of J.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Rowling's *Harry Potter* series and also the film adaptation of Philip Pullman's novel *Northern Lights* (the film bearing the title of the American edition of the book, *The Golden Compass*).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Distinctive features of the college's architecture have been used as models by a number of other academic institutions, including the NUI Galway, which reproduces Tom Quad.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The University of Chicago, Cornell University, and Kneuterdijk Palace have reproductions of Christ Church's dining hall (in the forms of Hutchinson Hall, the dining hall of Risley Residential College, and the Gothic hall of Kneuterdijk Palace, respectively).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] ChristChurch Cathedral in New Zealand, after which the City of Christchurch is named, is itself named after Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Stained glass windows in the cathedral and other buildings are by the Pre-Raphaelite William Morris group with designs by Edward Burne-Jones.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Historically, there has been a resident tortoise for the annual Oxford tortoise races.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] However, since 2020, due to the pandemic, there has not been a tortoise.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Recently, there have been two "resident" ducks, which can be seen in Tom Quad, affectionately named "Tom" and "Peck" after two of the famous quadrangles in Christ Church.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The Mercury fountain also houses carp, notably a large koi carp named George, which was a gift from the Empress of Japan.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] A heron may also be frequently seen visiting the pond as their hunting ground.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] This stopped, in September 2022, when the fishes were moved to a spacious lake home somewhere in Oxfordshire while the College perform essential maintenance on the pond.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Outside the Meadow Building in the Christ Church Meadow, there are also cows present during the day.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The cows are of rare English Longhorn breed.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Long associated with high church Anglicanism, Christ Church is unique in that it has both a cathedral choir and a college choir.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The cathedral choir comprises twelve adults and sixteen boys.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The adults are made up of lay clerks and choral scholars, or academical clerks.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The choir was all male until 2019, when they welcomed alto Elizabeth Nurse, the first female clerk of Christ Church Cathedral Choir.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The boys, whose ages range from eight to thirteen, are chosen for their musical ability and attend Christ Church Cathedral School.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Aside from the director, Peter Holder, there is also a sub-organist and two organ scholars.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college choir, however, is always a student-run society, and sings Evensong once a week in term time.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] In vacations the services are sung by the Cathedral Singers of Christ Church – a choir drawn from semi-professional singers in and around Oxford.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The cathedral also hosts visiting choirs from time to time during vacations.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Throughout its history, the cathedral choir has attracted many distinguished composers and organists – from its first director, John Taverner, appointed by Cardinal Wolsey in 1526, to William Walton in the twentieth century.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] In recent years, the choir have commissioned recorded works by contemporary composers such as John Tavener, William Mathias and Howard Goodall, also patron of Christ Church Music Society.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The choir, which broadcasts regularly, have many recordings to their credit and were the subject of the Channel 4 television documentary *Howard Goodall's Great Dates* (2002).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The documentary was nominated at the Montreux TV Festival in the arts programme category – and has since been seen internationally.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The choir's collaboration with Goodall has also led to their singing his TV themes for *Mr.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] They appeared in *Howard Goodall's Big Bangs*, broadcast in the United Kingdom on Channel 4 in March 2000.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] *Treasures of Christ Church* (2011) is an example of the choir's recording and debuted as the highest new entry in the UK Specialist Classical chart.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The disc featured on BBC Radio 3's *In Tune* on 26 September 2011 and on Radio 3's *Breakfast Show* on 27 September that year.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Christ Church holds one of the most important private collections of drawings in the UK, including works by Leonardo da Vinci, Raphael and Michelangelo.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The collection is composed of approximately 300 paintings and 2,000 drawings, a rotated selection of which are available to the public for viewing in the purpose-built Christ Church Picture Gallery.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Many of the works were bequeathed by a former member of the college, General John Guise (1682/3-1765), enabling the creation of the first public art gallery in Britain.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college arms are those of Cardinal Wolsey and were granted to him by the College of Arms on 4 August 1525.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] They are blazoned: *Sable, on a cross engrailed argent, between four leopards' faces azure a lion passant gules; on a chief or between two Cornish choughs proper a rose gules barbed vert and seeded or*.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The lion refers to Leo X who created Wolsey a Cardinal.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The arms are depicted beneath a red cardinal's galero with fifteen tassels on either side, and sometimes in front of two crossed croziers.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] There are also arms in use by the cathedral, which were confirmed in a visitation of 1574.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The first part of the grace is read by a scholar or exhibitioner before formal hall each evening, ending with the words *Per Iēsum Christum Dominum nostrum* ("Through Jesus Christ our Lord.") The remainder of the grace, replacing *Per Iēsum Christum* etc., is usually only read on special occasions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] There is also a long postprandial grace intended for use after meals, but this is rarely used.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] When High Table rises (by which time the Hall is largely empty), the senior member on High Table simply says *Benedictō benedīcātur* ("Let the Blessed One be blessed", or "Let a blessing be given by the Blessed One"), instead of the college postprandial grace.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] As well as rooms for accommodation, the buildings of Christ Church include the cathedral, one of the smallest in England, which also acts as the college chapel, a great hall, two libraries, two bars, and separate common rooms for dons, graduates and undergraduates.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] There are also gardens and a neighbouring sports ground and boat-house.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Accommodation is usually provided for all undergraduates, and for some graduates, although some accommodation is off-site.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Accommodation is generally spacious with most rooms equipped with sinks and fridges.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Many undergraduate rooms comprise 'sets' of bedrooms and living areas.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Members are generally expected to dine in hall, where there are two sittings every evening, one informal and one formal (where gowns must be worn and Latin grace is read).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college offers subsidies on the costs of accommodation and dinners for UK and ROI students from families with lower household incomes.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The buttery next to the Hall serves drinks around dinner time.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] There is also a college bar (known as the Undercroft), as well as a Junior Common Room (JCR) and a Graduate Common Room (GCR), equivalent to the Middle Common Room (MCR) in other colleges.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] There is a college lending library that supplements the university libraries (many of which are non-lending).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Law students have the additional facility of the Burn Law Library, named for Edward Burn.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Most undergraduate tutorials are carried out in the college, though for some specialist subjects undergraduates may be sent to tutors in other colleges.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Croquet is played in the Masters' Garden in the summer.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The sports ground is mainly used for netball, cricket, tennis, rugby and football and includes Christ Church cricket ground.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] In recent years the Christ Church Netball Club, which competes on the inter-college level in both mixed and women's matches, has become known as a popular and inclusive sport.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Rowing and punting is carried out by the boat-house across Christ Church Meadow – the Christ Church Boat Club is traditionally strong at rowing, having been Head of the River more than all other colleges except Oriel College.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college also owns its own punts which may be borrowed by students or dons.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] The college beagle pack (Christ Church and Farley Hill Beagles), which was formerly one of several undergraduate packs in Oxford, is no longer formally connected with the college or the university but continues to be staffed and followed by some Oxford undergraduates.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Also included in: Vaughan Williams's *An Oxford Elegy* (1947–49) and Hilary Mantel's Wolf Hall trilogy (referred to by its previous name, Cardinal College).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Notable former students of the college have included politicians, scientists, philosophers, entertainers and academics.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Thirteen British prime ministers have studied at the college including, Anthony Eden (Prime Minister 1955–1957), William Ewart Gladstone (1828–1831), Sir Robert Peel (1841–1846) and Archibald Primrose (1894–1895).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] From outside the UK, politicians from Canada (Ted Jolliffe), Pakistan (Zulfikar Ali Bhutto), Sri Lanka (S.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Bandaranaike), Pakistan (Bilawal Bhutto Zardari) and the United States (Charles Cotesworth Pinckney) have attended the college.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Prominent philosophers including John Locke, John Rawls, A.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Ayer, Gilbert Ryle, Michael Dummett, John Searle and Daniel Dennett studied at Christ Church.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Two Olympic rowing gold medallists studied at the college: Jonny Searle and Spanish Civil War volunteer Lewis Clive.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] In the sciences, polymath and natural philosopher Robert Hooke, developmental biologist John B.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Albert Einstein was a learned research fellow.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/christ-church-oxford] Auden, and the former officer of arms Hubert Chesshyre are other notable students to have previously studied at Christ Church.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] Chapman was born in Wells, Norfolk but moved with his family to Manchester and attended Manchester Grammar School.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] He then went to Christ Church, Oxford, obtaining degrees in chemistry (1893, 1st class) and physics (1894, 2nd class).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] Campman was by reputation something of a scientific recluse, difficult to dislodge from his laboratory, although he did play a full part in University and College affairs.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] Away from his teaching and research, he was reserved and somewhat eccentric, but enjoyed golf, cycling and walking.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] He married one of his research students, Muriel Holmes (a member of the university's Society of Oxford Home-Students) in 1918 and together they had a daughter, Ruth.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] He died from cancer at his home in Oxford in 1958.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] Chapman was a science master at Giggleswick School for a time before becoming a member of staff at the University of Manchester.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] In 1907, Jesus College, Oxford appointed him as fellow and tutor in charge of its new teaching and research laboratory.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] Chapman ran this until his retirement in 1944; the laboratory, the last college-run laboratory in the university, closed in 1947.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] Chapman was also vice-principal of the college (1926–44).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] Although Chapman took a keen interest in his students, research was his main priority.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] Chapman had a particular interest in the photochemical reaction of hydrogen and chlorine, establishing that minute traces of impurities caused unexpected consequences.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] He suggested the steady state hypothesis in 1913.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/david-chapman-chemist] He discovered that the interruption of light by a rotating sector caused the rate of the reaction to vary with the frequency of the sector and, in 1926, he was the first to apply this theory to measure the 'mean life' of a reaction intermediate.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Detonations occur in both conventional solid and liquid explosives, as well as in reactive gases.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] TNT, dynamite, and C4 are examples of high power explosives that detonate.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] The velocity of detonation in solid and liquid explosives is much higher than that in gaseous ones, which allows the wave system to be observed with greater detail (higher resolution).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] A very wide variety of fuels may occur as gases (e.g. hydrogen), droplet fogs, or dust suspensions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] In addition to dioxygen, oxidants can include halogen compounds, ozone, hydrogen peroxide, and oxides of nitrogen.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Gaseous detonations are often associated with a mixture of fuel and oxidant in a composition somewhat below conventional flammability ratios.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] They happen most often in confined systems, but they sometimes occur in large vapor clouds.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Other materials, such as acetylene, ozone, and hydrogen peroxide, are detonable in the absence of an oxidant (or reductant).
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] In these cases the energy released results from the rearrangement of the molecular constituents of the material.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Detonation was discovered in 1881 by four French scientists Marcellin Berthelot and Paul Marie Eugène Vieille and Ernest-François Mallard and Henry Louis Le Chatelier.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] The mathematical predictions of propagation were carried out first by David Chapman in 1899 and by Émile Jouguet in 1905, 1906 and 1917.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] The next advance in understanding detonation was made by John von Neumann and Werner Döring in the early 1940s and Yakov B.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Zel'dovich and Aleksandr Solomonovich Kompaneets in the 1960s.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] The simplest theory to predict the behaviour of detonations in gases is known as the Chapman–Jouguet (CJ) condition, developed around the turn of the 20th century.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] This theory, described by a relatively simple set of algebraic equations, models the detonation as a propagating shock wave accompanied by exothermic heat release.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Such a theory describes the chemistry and diffusive transport processes as occurring abruptly as the shock passes.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] A more complex theory was advanced during World War II independently by Zel'dovich, von Neumann, and Döring.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] This theory, now known as ZND theory, admits finite-rate chemical reactions and thus describes a detonation as an infinitesimally thin shock wave, followed by a zone of exothermic chemical reaction.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] With a reference frame of a stationary shock, the following flow is subsonic, so that an acoustic reaction zone follows immediately behind the lead front, the Chapman–Jouguet condition.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] There is also some evidence that the reaction zone is semi-metallic in some explosives.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Both theories describe one-dimensional and steady wavefronts.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] However, in the 1960s, experiments revealed that gas-phase detonations were most often characterized by unsteady, three-dimensional structures, which can only, in an averaged sense, be predicted by one-dimensional steady theories.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] The Wood-Kirkwood detonation theory can correct some of these limitations.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Experimental studies have revealed some of the conditions needed for the propagation of such fronts.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] In confinement, the range of composition of mixes of fuel and oxidant and self-decomposing substances with inerts are slightly below the flammability limits and, for spherically expanding fronts, well below them.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] The influence of increasing the concentration of diluent on expanding individual detonation cells has been elegantly demonstrated.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Similarly, their size grows as the initial pressure falls.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Since cell widths must be matched with minimum dimension of containment, any wave overdriven by the initiator will be quenched.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Mathematical modeling has steadily advanced to predicting the complex flow fields behind shocks inducing reactions.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] To date, none has adequately described how the structure is formed and sustained behind unconfined waves.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] When used in explosive devices, the main cause of damage from a detonation is the supersonic blast front (a powerful shock wave) in the surrounding area.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] This is a significant distinction from deflagrations where the exothermic wave is subsonic and maximum pressures for non-metal specks of dust are approximately 7–10 times atmospheric pressure.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Therefore, detonation is a feature for destructive purposes while deflagration is favored for the acceleration of firearms' projectiles.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] However, detonation waves may also be used for less destructive purposes, including deposition of coatings to a surface or cleaning of equipment (e.g. slag removal) and even explosively welding together metals that would otherwise fail to fuse.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Pulse detonation engines use the detonation wave for aerospace propulsion.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] The first flight of an aircraft powered by a pulse detonation engine took place at the Mojave Air & Space Port on January 31, 2008.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Unintentional detonation when deflagration is desired is a problem in some devices.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] In Otto cycle, or gasoline engines it is called engine knocking or pinging, and it causes a loss of power.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] It can also cause excessive heating, and harsh mechanical shock that can result in eventual engine failure.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] In firearms, it may cause catastrophic and potentially lethal failure.
[src:david-chapman-chemist/detonation] Pulse detonation engines are a form of pulsed jet engine that has been experimented with on several occasions as this offers the potential for good fuel efficiency.
